<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix</i> <i>lasiolepis</i> are dominant or co-dominant in the tall shrub or low tree canopy with <i>Acer</i> <i>macrophyllum</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>salicifolia</i>, <i>Cephalanthus</i> <i>occidentalis</i>, <i>Cornus</i> <i>sericea</i>, <i>Morella</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Platanus</i> <i>racemosa</i>, <i>Populus</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Populus</i> <i>trichocarpa</i>, <i>Salix</i> spp. and <i>Sambucus</i> <i>nigra</i>. As a shrubland, emergent trees may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Plants < 10 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Salix lasiolepis</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub or tree canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a, Evens and San 2005, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix lasiolepis</i> ≥ 25% absolute cover in the shrub or tree canopy (Potter 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix lasiolepis</i> is >30% relative cover in the shrub layer (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix lasiolepis</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy, or > 30% relative cover with <i>Rubus</i> (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stream banks and benches, slope seeps, and stringers along drainages. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Salix lasiolepis</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
