<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix lasiolepis </i>is a riparian tall shrub or tree up to 8 m in height. Leaves are glaucous on the lower surface and elliptical to ovate in shape. The varieties (Argus 1997) have somewhat different ranges: var. <i>bigelovii </i>is a coastal plant, and var. <i>lasiolepis </i>grows throughout the state. Leaves of many plants on the North Coast suggest hybridization with <i>S. hookeriana. <br/>
<br/>
Salix lasiolepis </i>grows on seasonally or intermittently flooded riparian sites. Some plants in the California stands are sufficiently tall to be trees. Plants are typically shrubby and multi-branched along coastal creeks, at lower and middle elevations, and in parts of the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta. We include both forms in this alliance. Disturbances during winter floods modify stands; timing of seed dispersal and spring flood patterns determine seedling success. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
