    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands are common in Golden Gate National Recreation Area, in the East Bay Hills, and as far as Carmel River.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). Stands in the Diablo Range, at Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012), and elsewhere as far south as the Santa Maria River occupy recently disturbed areas from the windswept outer coast to more protected inland locations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Small stands occasionally occur along lower reaches creeks throughout the section, including Thomes Creek, and in drainage ditches and road cuts in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Stands where <i>S. lasiolepis</i> is co-dominant with <i>S. exigua</i> are in <i>Salix exigua</i> alliance (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007). <i>S. lasiolepis</i> is also a secondary species in <i>Populus fremontii, Salix exigua,</i> and <i>Salix lucida</i> alliances along the Sacramento River (Vaghti 2003, Vaghti and Greco 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac, Ai, Am, Ar). <i>S. lasiolepis</i> mixes with other willows in this and several other alliances in the southern portion of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-p). Stands exist in Modoc and Lassen National Forests (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ac-d, Ag, Al, An). Stands are scattered along the larger rivers and in some of the major springs. Much of the desert does not appear to have stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dd-f, Dh-l). Stands occur along most of the creeks at mid to lower elevations in the section. An association with <i>Rosa woodsii</i> occurs from the Spring Mountains in Nevada (Manning and Padgett 1995). Similar stands are to be expected in this section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ab-d, Af-g, Ai-m). Stands occur in permanently moist, riparian settings along streams, seeps, and swamps; some form a windswept scrub in Marin Co. (Evens and Kentner 2006 Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). Those on the northern Point Reyes Peninsula contain hybrids with <i>S. hookeriana.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). Stands are common along several major streams and rivers in the section and reach to at least 1000 m in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1974).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Stands exist along intermittent and permanent streams.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bc-e). Stands occur at Honey Lake and several other basins in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-n, Ep-t). Stands are scattered on both the eastern and western sides of the section up to at least 1900 m. The best descriptions of stands come from Potter (2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Nearly pure stands of small to medium size occupy stream bank and floodplain settings (Potter 2005, Klein et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands are common at springs and in well-watered canyons below about 1800 m throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands exist along riparian corridors and stream terraces in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) and Santa Catalina Island (D. Knapp, pers. comm. 2007). Those on Santa Cruz Island have been mapped (TNC 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). Stands exist as high as 1800 m in Anza- Borrego State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and in the Volcan Mountain area of the Peninsular Ranges (Evens and San 2005). Zembal (1989) reported tree density and cover along Santa Ana and Santa Margarita rivers. Stromberg and Patten (1992) reported willow density for stands in Transverse Ranges.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-e, Dg-j, Dl-m). Stands occur at mid to lower elevations in this section.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix lasiolepis </i>easily colonizes moist ditches where it is “weedy” and removed by flood-control districts and other agencies. The species is valuable for bank and slope stabilization. </div>
</div>

    

    

